back downtown , the execs squeeze in a few meeting at the hotel before board the bus again .
this time , it be for dinner and dance -- a block away .
under the star and moon of the renovate indiana roof ballroom , nine of the hottest chef in town feed them indiana duckling mousseline , lobster consomme , veal mignon and chocolate terrine with a raspberry sauce .
know a tasty -- and free -- meal when they eat one , the executive give the chef a stand ovation .
more than a few ceos say the red - carpet treatment tempt them to return to a heartland city for future meeting .
but for now , they 're look forward to their winter meet -- boca in february .
south korea register a trade deficit of $ 101 million in october , reflect the country 's economic sluggishness , accord to government figure release wednesday .
preliminary tally by the trade and industry ministry show another trade deficit in october , the fifth monthly setback this year , cast a cloud on south korea 's export - orient economy .
export in october stood at $ 5.29 billion , a mere 0.7 % increase from a year earlier , while import increase sharply to $ 5.39 billion , up 20 % from last october .
south korea 's economic boom , which begin in 1986 , stop this year because of prolong labor dispute , trade conflict and sluggish export .
government official say export at the end of the year would remain under a government target of $ 68 billion .
despite the gloomy forecast , south korea have record a trade surplus of $ 71 million so far this year .
from january to october , the nation 's accumulate export increase 4 % from the same period last year to $ 50.45 billion .
import be at $ 50.38 billion , up 19 % .
newsweek , try to keep pace with rival time magazine , announce new advertise rate for 1990 and say it will introduce a new incentive plan for advertiser .
the new ad plan from newsweek , a unit of the washington post co. , be the second incentive plan the magazine have offer advertiser in three year .
plan that give advertiser discount for maintain or increase ad spend have become permanent fixture at the news weekly and underscore the fierce competition between newsweek , time warner inc. 's time magazine , and mortimer b. zuckerman 's u.s. news & world report .
alan spoon , recently name newsweek president , say newsweek 's ad rate would increase 5 % in january .
a full , four - color page in newsweek will cost $ 100,980 .
when the soviet union collapse in 1991 , partisan of ronald reagan claim he have " won " the cold war .
although a careful review of the fact will show it be not true , the claim be that the soviet union become overextended attempt to keep up with ray @-@ gun 's defense spend .
pappy bush , who be the president at the time , claim that he have win the cold war since the collapse of the soviet union happen on his watch .
regardless of how one view those claim , for many people -- capitalist especially -- herald the " victory " of capitalism .
globalism be hail by its partisan as the natural consequence of their " victory , " and the sensible way to bring the alleged blessing of a problematic freedom to the people of the world .
always impatient of any restaint , capitalist use this so @-@ call victory as justification for the opposition to , or call for the roll @-@ back of any regulatory restraint .
but not everyone have agree with that view of the world and of economic system .
now , with the various " occupy " movement , it be ( or ought to be ) obvious that a great many people be less than enchant with capitalism and its expression in the idustrial democracy , as well as in the country into which capitalist from the industrial democracy go to invest .
what be your thought on capitalism and its activity ?
@setanta , unfettered capitalism have yield an oligarchy .
governmental regulation be good for capitalisms evolution .
health and safety and environmental horror need to be regulate otherwise industry will not ever do whats right for humanity .
@setanta , i do n't have a problem with capitalism -- i have a problem with unregulated capitalism .
i agree with this completely .
capitalism thrive when everyone understand the rule , play by the rule and enforce the rule .
if everyone have to spend all their time try to circumvent the rule , understand the rule or fight against those not follow the rule , that be where trouble really begin .
that 's the problem with " deregulation ".
remove rule do n't help business be more competitive , it mean that business must race to the bottom to counter new business that start there .
it 's like change the rule to monopoly half way through the game so that all the previous purchase be meaningless .
that 's not a benefit to capitalism despite what some would tell you .
